    <segment id="1" parent="38" relname="span">My thoughts are that how intuitive an interface might be is based entirely on its 
audience.  </segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="28" relname="span">

Individual differences can be grouped into four categories: </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="26" relname="list">(1) knowledge, 
experience, and skill; </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="26" relname="list">(2) personality factors;</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="26" relname="list"> (3) physical and demographic attributes; </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="26" relname="list">
and (4) user levels (Badre et al, 2002).</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="1" relname="elaboration">

A working definition of intuitiveness could be the probability that a defined inexperienced 
user can intuitively figure out how to do a defined set of tasks correctly (ConfirmIt, 2004).</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="39" relname="span">

To measure intuitiveness, we would have different levels of interfaces:</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="29" relname="list">
General users (mp3 players, DVD players, e-mail programs)</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="29" relname="list">
Sophisticated Users (video games, mp3 ripping, paint programs)</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="29" relname="list">
Professional Users (Photoshop, accounting, music recording)</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="29" relname="list">
Extreme Professionals (AutoCad, video game developers, programming languages)</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="15" relname="nonvolitional-cause">

Since everyone brings different levels of intelligence and historical knowledge with them 
to the table, </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="30" relname="span">
it would be best to determine how intuitive an interface is by using sample 
groups of users of various skill levels.</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="31" relname="list">

Everyone who uses a general user type program should be able to figure it out with 
minimum effort.  </segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="31" relname="list">
Also, most of the architects in a sample group should be able to do the 
basic functions of a new CAD application.  </segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="31" relname="nonvolitional-result">
When these fail, then the interface could be 
deemed (gasp) unintuitive. </segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="35" relname="span">

One could set up matrices that say:</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="36" relname="span">
Tasks A, and B are very simple everyone should be able to do this.  </segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="20" relname="elaboration">
Ex: Start and Stop 
the CD-player.</segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="23" relname="concession">
Task C is a little harder,</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="34" relname="span"> but assuming a good intuitive interface, everyone should be able 
to do this, too.  </segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="23" relname="elaboration">
Ex: Eject the CD or get a play list.</segment>
    <segment id="25" parent="33" relname="list">
And so on.</segment>
